+Yuxz Wzxy If you read into the history of shuttle and ISS, you'll see that 
there are some in the science community who are opposed to the expense of 
manned spaceflight and do question the value of the experiments done on the 
ISS. Prestige and politics play into the justification of the station. But 
the wealth of engineering understanding and experience coming from it will 
be a benefit when developing technologies for future long distance, long 
duration human spaceflight.

But "is it worth it?" is a legitimate question. "Is it real?" is absurd. 
Especially in this video where Steve Blakey's arguments come down to 
nothing more than "the station and the astronauts don't look like how I 
think they should look." He obviously hasn't bothered to do real research 
or even any serious reading on the ISS, Many of the questions he raises -- 
how waste is handled, the shape of reentry vehicles, the overall design of 
the station -- are answered in detail, both on various websites and in any 
number of books. Instead of using his curiosity to drive him to learn, he 
jumped to his own conclusions and posted it on the web. It is galling when 
he says things like "they just built it ad hoc...they didn't really think 
about it" when you appreciate how much engineering ingenuity went into the 
ISS.

The temporature on the moon is +392 to -328 degrees Fahrenheit. All trips 
on to the Moon’s surface were carefully planned for lunar dawn, to ensure 
the surface hadn’t had time to heat up fully to its daytime temperature.

What we commonly think of as "temperature" in our environment is air 
temperature. So when you say, "Today it was 75 F in Los Angeles," what 
you're saying is that the air was 75 F. The hot pavement in the parking lot 
may have been 150 F. And the concrete floor of the bottom level of a 
parking garage may be 60 F. That is, each item in an environment doesn't 
all come to the same temperature.

But more importantly, there's no air on the Moon. So air temperature is 
meaningless. The surface may get very hot, but that doesn't mean everything 
nearby will get that hot. How hot something gets in space depends largely 
on how much heat it absorbs from the sun. The lunar soil absorbs 85-90% of 
the solar energy (1300 watts max per square meter) that falls on it. So 
when the sun shines most directly on it it -- lunar noon -- it's sucking up 
a lot of heat.

A space suit, on the other hand, absorbs only about 15% of the solar energy 
that falls on it. And the outer layers are heavily insulated from the inner 
layers. Aluminum absorbs only about 5% of the solar heat. Things made of 
aluminum don't always heat up very much in space.

An astronaut's boots touch the surface directly and so absorb heat from it. 
But again, insulation is the key. You can walk very easily in ordinary 
shoes across asphalt that's 150 F or more without any ill effects. Your 
shoe soles get hot, but little of that heat conducts to your feet. Same 
with the astronauts. They had about an inch total of boot sole between them 
and the ground.

Articles of the Antarctic Treaty

continue;

territorial sovereignty claims; no new claims shall be asserted while the 
treaty is in force;

Article 5 – The treaty prohibits nuclear explosions or disposal of 
radioactive wastes;

surrounding waters south of 60 degrees 00 minutes south;

observation, to any area and may inspect all stations, installations, and 
equipment; advance notice of all activities and of the introduction of 
military personnel must be given;

Article 8 – Allows for good jurisdiction over observers and scientists by 
their own states;

Article 9 – Frequent consultative meetings take place among member nations;

Article 10 – All treaty states will discourage activities by any country in 
Antarctica that are contrary to the treaty;

Article 11 – All disputes to be settled peacefully by the parties concerned 
or, ultimately, by the International Court of Justice;

Articles 12, 13, 14 – Deal with upholding, interpreting, and amending the 
treaty among involved nations.

The main objective of the ATS is to ensure in the interests of all 
humankind that Antarctica shall continue forever to be used exclusively for 
peaceful purposes and shall not become the scene or object of international 
discord.

About re-entry vehicles. First: every body that produces a pressure 
differential during atmospheric flight produces lift. Second thing to note, 
the center of mass is at the lowest place possible, near the heat shield. 
This way the craft is aerodynamically stable because the most drag is 
produced at the top. Compare it with the shape of a falling rain drop. 
Third: the center of mass is off center of the vehicle, so the atmospheric 
drag pulls the craft a bit to one side. This small tilt produces the 
pressure differential needed and so the whole thing becomes a lifting body. 
Fourth: the guidance computer or in case of failure the pilot orients the 
vehicle by rolling, hereby changing the direction of lift. This way the 
vehicle can be steered for the optimum descent trajectory. Don't believe 
me? Download fluid dynamics simulation software and recreate it yourself. 
Otherwise there are other products to simulate those conditions: X-Plane 
and Kerbal Space Program with the FAR extension.﻿

Responding from 3:15 since you're summarizing:

 Liquid waste is collected in 20-litre (5.3 US gal) containers and 
recycled. Solid waste is collected in individual micro-perforated bags 
which are stored in an aluminum container (exposed to vacuum to kill 
bacteria and prevent odors). Full containers are transferred to Progress 
for disposal.(Progress is a Russian made un-manned cargo transport which 
supplies the station and then burns up on re-entry, along with the waste 
which has been stored in it).

As for general cleaning, the astronauts clean surfaces and dust on a daily 
bases, and the physico-chemical life support system has to:
1) de-moisturize the air (it feeds the water back into the water-cycle), 
2) reduce and/or remove Carbon Dioxide (using e. g. Molecular Sieves and 
Sabatier; a part of the CO2 is vented into space), 
3) generate Oxygen (e. g. from water with electrolysis), 
4) generate Nitrogen (mostly coming from tanks), 
5) check for hazardous gases / particles and traces of fire (I remember an 
"electronic nose" being tested onboard the ISS though there are other 
sensors as well), 
6) remove (if possible) any hazardous or excess gases and particles (not 
only dust) from the cabin air with filters, charcoal beds, chemisorbant 
beds, and catalytic burners, 
7) and last but not least, circulate the air because if there is no 
gravity, you have no convection which leads to "dead zones"
Among other things.

Going to respond to a few issues at random place in the video:

Van Allen belt: the radioactive particles only make up a small portion of 
the belt, and is mostly alpha particles which can't even penetrate the 
outer layer of skin, let alone a shielded space station.

Re-entry burn up: The reason some vehicles burn up and others don't, is 
because the latter carry heat shields in the form of ceramic plating.

Re-entry capsule tumble: The capsule is perfectly stable during re-entry, 
assuming that it is flown correctly, re-entry vectors are carefully 
calculated.

Moon landing: I can see how this is hard to believe, given your 
misconceptions about space travel, but we have been to the moon, there has 
been 100 missions to the moon (although only a fraction of them manned).
If you get the right equipment you can even shoot a laser at the 
retro-reflector left on the surface, and see it ping back at your detector.

This is not an exhaustive list of issues and misconceptions i've observed 
in this video, but i've run out of time.

stating it as i see it.

more and be objective about it.

The laser reflectors left on the moon's surface, which are touted by Apollo 
believers are hard evidence of the Apollo Moon Landings, are not. First, 
lasers were already being bounced off the moon's surface before the Apollo 
landings were alleged to take place. The Dec 1966 issue of National 
Geographic reported that scientists at MIT were doing just that. In fact, 
radio waves were being bounced off the moon as early as the 1950's. Here is 
a screen shot of the article in that issue describing it: (for some reason, 
I am not able to embed it below)
 
http://s9.postimage.org/a10sw4qd9/National_Geographic_December_1966_p876_small.jpg
 
Second, laser reflectors were dropped on the moon by unmanned probes by 
both the US and Soviet Union. Here are two examples of Soviet unmanned 
probes leaving laser reflectors, as described by Wikipedia:
 
http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lunokhod_1
http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lunokhod_2  
Thus this argument is not hard evidence for the authenticity of the Apollo 
Moon Landings. For more info about the laser reflectors, see Jarrah White's 
FAQ: http://moonfaker.com/faqs.html and his YouTube videos entitled 
?Moonfaker laser reflectors?.

In case you're not:

First of all, the albedo of the moon is 0.12, meaning that it reflects 12% 
of the suns light

As a comparison, worn asphalt has an albedo of 0.12, green grass has an 
albedo of 0.25 and desert sand has an albedo of 0.4.

I wouldn't classify the moon as highly reflective.

Secondly, diffusion, light spreads out a lot when it's reflected from a 
non-uniform surface, like the dust of the moon.

Even if the moon was a perfect mirror, you would not be able to use it to 
reflect a laser directly back to your location, unless you can hit a spot 
that is perfectly perpendicular to your location, it would however still 
diffuse by a bit, since the moon is spherical.

A retro-reflector however, will reflect light back at its source,

You dont need a retro-reflector to reflect laser beams from the moon, 
because the moon dust itself is highly reflective. The whole moon is a 
reflector, how else could we see the sunlight at night reflected from the 
moon to the earth.
